   :author: Kevin Austin
   :difficulty: 1
   :basecourse: thinkcspy
   :topic: Debugging/Exercises
   :from_source: F
   :multiple_answers:
   :random:
   :answer_a: Write all code first then tackle each error message as it happens
   :feedback_a: No.  This is a good way to get stuck.
   :answer_b: Go back and change code that you tested previously
   :feedback_b: This will risk creating more problems.
   :answer_c: Depend on your memory without writing things down
   :feedback_c: The best strategy is to keep track of issues as they occur by writing them down
   :answer_d: Make progress by improving your code one step at a time and testing each improvement
   :feedback_d: Yes.  Incremental progress will help build confidence.  Make only one change per iteration.
   :answer_e: Get code from the internet.  Why reinvent the wheel?
   :feedback_e: No.  Reading is good.  Copying without understanding will not be helpful.
   :correct: d

